# One-to-Many Mapping in Hibernate:

    In any real-world application, we often see relationships where one entity is connected to many others.

    Think about a student in a school:
        1. A student can enroll in multiple courses.
        2. Each course, in turn, belongs to a single student.

    This type of relationship is known as One-to-Many.

    In Hibernate, One-to-Many Mapping allows us to link one Java object to multiple related objects and store them neatly in the
    database. Instead of writing complicated SQL queries, Hibernate helps manage these relationships through simple annotations.

    In this guide, we will build a small project step by step to understand how One-to-Many Mapping works in Hibernate.

Q1. What is One-to-Many Mapping?
Standard Definition
    One-to-Many Mapping in Hibernate is a relationship where a single record in one table is associated with multiple records in another table.

Q2. Why Use One-to-Many Mapping?
    If we were doing this manually in a database:
    We would have to handle foreign keys, join queries, and maintain consistency.

    Hibernate simplifies this:
        1. You work with Java objects directly.
        2. Hibernate takes care of database operations.
        3. Relationships are defined once and managed automatically.

