    Step 1: Set Up the Database
            To store information about students and the courses they take, we need to set up some tables in the MySQL database.
            Use this simple command to create the database:

                CREATE DATABASE KodnestDb;
                USE KodnestDb;

                CREATE TABLE kodneststudent (
                    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
                    name VARCHAR(50),
                    email VARCHAR(50),
                    phone VARCHAR(15)
                );
                CREATE TABLE course (
                    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
                    course_name VARCHAR(50),
                    student_id INT,
                    FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES kodneststudent(id)
                );

Step 5: Define Entity Classes
        5.1. Course Entity
              The Course class is like the notebook where we keep details about each course that a student is taking:

                        package com.kodnest.entity;
                        import jakarta.persistence.*;

                        @Entity
                        @Table(name = "course")
                        public class Course {
                            @Id
                            @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
                            private int id;

                            @Column(name = "course_name", length = 50, nullable = false)
                            private String courseName;

                            // Many courses can belong to one student
                            @ManyToOne
                            @JoinColumn(name = "student_id")
                            private KodnestStudent student;

                            // Getters and Setters
                            public int getId()
                            {
                            return id;
                            }
                            public void setId(int id)
                             {
                             this.id = id;
                              }
                            public String getCourseName()
                            {
                            return courseName;
                             }
                            public void setCourseName(String courseName)
                            {
                            this.courseName = courseName;
                            }
                            public KodnestStudent getStudent()
                            {
                            return student;
                            }
                            public void setStudent(KodnestStudent student)
                            {
                            this.student = student;
                             }
                        }
        5.2. KodnestStudent Entity
             The KodnestStudent class is where we keep all the information about a student:
                        package com.kodnest.entity;
                        import jakarta.persistence.*;
                        import java.util.List;

                        @Entity
                        @Table(name = "kodneststudent")
                        public class KodnestStudent {
                            @Id
                            @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
                            private int id;

                            @Column(length = 50)
                            private String name;

                            @Column(length = 50)
                            private String email;

                            @Column(length = 15)
                            private String phone;

                            // One student can have many courses
                            @OneToMany(mappedBy = "student", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
                            private List<Course> courses;

                            // Getters and Setters
                            public int getId()
                            {
                            return id;
                            }
                            public void setId(int id)
                            {
                            this.id = id;
                            }
                            public String getName()
                            {
                            return name;
                             }
                            public void setName(String name)
                            {
                            this.name = name;
                            }
                            public String getEmail()
                            {
                            return email;
                            }
                            public void setEmail(String email)
                           {
                           this.email = email;
                           }
                            public String getPhone()
                            {
                            return phone;
                             }
                            public void setPhone(String phone)
                            {
                            this.phone = phone;
                            }
                            public List<Course> getCourses()
                             {
                             return courses;
                             }
                            public void setCourses(List<Course> courses)
                             {
                             this.courses = courses;
                              }
                        }

Step 6: Write the Main Class (OneToManyExample.java)
        This is the heart of our program. This class helps us create a student and enroll them in multiple courses:

            package com.kodnest.main;

            import com.kodnest.entity.Course;
            import com.kodnest.entity.KodnestStudent;
            import org.hibernate.Session;
            import org.hibernate.SessionFactory;
            import org.hibernate.Transaction;
            import org.hibernate.cfg.Configuration;

            import java.util.ArrayList;
            import java.util.List;

            public class OneToManyExample {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                    // Create a SessionFactory to connect to the database
                    SessionFactory sessionFactory = new Configuration().configure().buildSessionFactory();

                    // Create a new student
                    KodnestStudent student = new KodnestStudent();
                    student.setName("Ravi Kumar");
                    student.setEmail("ravi.kumar@gmail.com");
                    student.setPhone("9876543210");

                    // Create courses that the student will take
                    Course course1 = new Course();
                    course1.setCourseName("Java");

                    Course course2 = new Course();
                    course2.setCourseName("Spring Boot");

                    // Associate the courses with the student
                    course1.setStudent(student);
                    course2.setStudent(student);

                    List<Course> courses = new ArrayList<>();
                    courses.add(course1);
                    courses.add(course2);
                    student.setCourses(courses);

                    // Open a session, begin a transaction, save the student and courses
                    Session session = sessionFactory.openSession();
                    Transaction transaction = session.beginTransaction();
                    session.persist(student);
                    transaction.commit();

                    System.out.println("Student and associated courses saved successfully!");

                    // Fetch and display the student and courses from the database
                    KodnestStudent fetchedStudent = session.get(KodnestStudent.class, student.getId());
                    System.out.println("Fetched Student Details:");
                    System.out.println("Name: " + fetchedStudent.getName());
                    System.out.println("Email: " + fetchedStudent.getEmail());
                    System.out.println("Phone: " + fetchedStudent.getPhone());

                    System.out.println("Courses Enrolled:");
                    for (Course course : fetchedStudent.getCourses()) {
                        System.out.println("- " + course.getCourseName());
                    }

                    session.close();
                    sessionFactory.close();
                }
            }

# Key Points to Remember:
    1. One-to-Many Mapping connects a single record in one table to multiple records in another table.
    2. Use @OneToMany in the parent entity (KodnestStudent) and @ManyToOne in the child entity (Course).
    3. The mappedBy attribute in @OneToMany indicates that the child entity manages the relationship.
    4. Adding cascade = CascadeType.ALL ensures that changes in the parent entity are automatically applied to the child entities.
    5. Always configure the database connection correctly in hibernate.cfg.xml to avoid runtime errors.

# Common Interview Questions and Answers:

    Q1: What is One-to-Many Mapping in Hibernate?
    Answer: One-to-Many Mapping is a relationship where one record in a table is connected to multiple records in another table.
            In Hibernate, this is achieved using @OneToMany and @ManyToOne annotations.

    Q2: Which annotations are used for One-to-Many Mapping?
    Answer: 1. @OneToMany: Used in the parent entity to indicate that it has multiple child entities.
            2. @ManyToOne: Used in the child entity to indicate that it belongs to a single parent entity.
            3. @JoinColumn: Defines the foreign key column in the child table.

    Q3: What is the use of cascade = CascadeType.ALL?
    Answer: It ensures that any operation performed on the parent entity (like save or delete) is automatically
            applied to all related child entities.

    Q4: How does Hibernate know which entity manages the relationship?
    Answer: By using the mappedBy attribute in @OneToMany, we tell Hibernate that the child entity is responsible for managing the relationship.

    Q5: Can One-to-Many Mapping exist without a foreign key?
    Answer: No. In the database, the child table must have a foreign key that refers to the parent table to maintain the relationship.

    Q6: What happens if you don’t use mappedBy?
    Answer: Hibernate will create a join table to manage the relationship, even if it is not required.

    Q7: Can a parent entity have zero child entities in One-to-Many Mapping?
    Answer: Yes. A parent entity can exist without any related child entities.